    "summary": "I am an independent legal specialist with demonstrated presence in the port and the maritime industry, available for legal advice and consultancy. \n\nMy primary focus is on:\n\u2022\tCybersecurity including NIS 2 Directive, developing legislation and regulations on the national and the local level, and implementing cybersecurity policies, guidelines and operations\n\u2022\tHow to govern port and maritime physical and digital infrastructures (including Port Community Systems)\n\u2022\tAnalyzing existing legal frameworks in context of modernization and implementation of new instruments\n\u2022\tGeneral legal topics (contracts, studying and analyzing legal documents)\n\nMain recent experiences: \n\u2022\tDeveloping Cybersecurity Guidelines for Ports and Port Facilities teaming up with specialists of IAPH (International Association of Ports and Harbors)\n\u2022\tImplementing cybersecurity policies, guidelines and operations (including NIS 2 Directive) in various entities \n\u2022\tRestructuring governance of port infrastructure and related activities for public entities\n\u2022\tAssignment World Bank for contributing to Global Report on Port Community Systems\n\u2022\tAssignment World Bank for contributing to Port Sector Law for the State of Lebanon \n\u2022\tChairing Cybersecurity Committee and participating in the Legal Committee of IAPH\n\u2022\tHead Legal of Havenbedrijf Rotterdam N.V.\n\nMy legal expertise combined with my drive, wit and communication skills, enables me to solve unique issues in complex environments. I am at my best in a position which combines legal expert knowledge and hands-on coordinating skills. I describe myself as a sincere, rational and dedicated analytic, and being able to navigate in both the public and the private sector.\nMy clients judge me as persistent, collaborative, result oriented and always aware of the strategic purpose of things to be done. \nThrough my honorary engagement into IAPH I am able to follow upfront the output (treaties, conventions, legislation, guidelines) of instrument making bodies (e.g. IMO, UNCITRAL, UNEP, UN/CEFACT, UNCTAD, World Bank, IMF), relevant for the port and maritime industry and to comment and act on these outputs. \n\nI hold a master\u2019s degree in civil and in public law from Erasmus University Rotterdam and with specializations in maritime law. With an additional master\u2019s degree in public administration from the Nederlandse School voor Openbaar Bestuur and Financial Master Classes for Lawyers at Nyenrode Business University, I am able to understand the strategic drivers of both public and private entities.",
